00:05:48.126 --> 00:05:54.746
things like outlawing, the forbidding, the use of non-core languages to

00:05:55.186 --> 00:05:59.356
actively persecuting speakers of different languages, there has been a

00:05:59.356 --> 00:06:05.996
lot of activity aimed specifically at killing off less popular languages.

00:06:06.676 --> 00:06:13.346
English, of course, is a prime example - the British Empire forced people to speak English,

00:06:13.526 --> 00:06:19.926
and the fact that the founding fathers of America were native English speakers and chose

00:06:19.956 --> 00:06:26.166
to write the constitution in English meant that other, native languages were pushed

00:06:26.216 --> 00:06:32.116
to one side, and English became the dominant language for the world's dominant power.

00:06:33.096 --> 00:06:36.206
If it weren’t for things like this, you probably wouldn’t be learning

00:06:36.216 --> 00:06:40.576
English, as it would never have reached such a globally dominant position.

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:48.016
But for centuries, the majority of people didn’t care about languages dying out.

00:06:48.586 --> 00:06:55.596
Languages die when their speakers die, and so, by default, if there aren’t any speakers

00:06:55.626 --> 00:07:01.156
of the language left then there aren’t many people that really care about that language.

00:07:01.656 --> 00:07:05.796
And globally, we don’t seem to really care about the

00:07:05.796 --> 00:07:08.746
fact that there are so many endangered languages.

00:07:09.546 --> 00:07:17.130
To be precise, according to UNESCO, at least 43% all languages spoken in the world

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:24.720
are endangered, more than half have fewer than 10,000 speakers, a quarter have

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:32.410
fewer than 1,000 speakers, and around 20 languages only have one speaker left.

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:38.130
Now, there are five different categories of ‘endangered languages’, ranging

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:43.010
from ‘vulnerable’, which means that most children can speak the language,

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:47.580
but it’s normally restricted to certain situations, normally just at home.

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:53.870
And the final category is ‘extinct’, meaning that there are no speakers left.

00:07:55.465 --> 00:08:00.580
And the sad thing is that, for a lot of these languages that are dying out,

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:07.190
when the last person dies, that’s it, you can’t just ‘turn it back on again’.

00:08:07.850 --> 00:08:13.580
As fewer and fewer people speak a language, it’s hard to reverse the decline.

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:20.360
Fewer children learn it, and the older people who do speak it won’t live forever.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:27.020
So purely from a ‘sands of time’ point of view, this situation

00:08:27.310 --> 00:08:33.070
naturally means that the number of speakers reduces, and tends to zero.

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:40.030
But also, the fewer speakers of a language that do exist, the fewer opportunities those

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:46.950
people have to speak that language, and as we all know, if you don’t actually use a language,

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:52.710
you start to speak less fluently in it, and you start to lose the language yourself.

00:08:53.410 --> 00:08:58.360
And if you are the only speaker of a language and you don’t have anyone left to

00:08:58.360 --> 00:09:04.470
practice with, well then that language is quickly on the path to becoming extinct.

00:09:06.130 --> 00:09:11.020
There was a story a few years ago about a village in Mexico where

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:16.100
there were only two speakers left of a language called Ayapaneco.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:22.260
So the only people that they could practice Ayapaneco with were each other.

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:29.180
