00:10:10.990 --> 00:10:17.600
However, the situation it was talking about certainly does exist - when people don’t

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:23.490
have anyone to practice a language with, and if they haven’t taught anyone else that

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:29.620
language, then that language goes to the grave with the death of its last speaker.

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:36.410
Unless there has been a conscious effort to protect it, and to get a generation

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:41.830
of new speakers speaking that language, then this is exactly what happens.

00:10:42.803 --> 00:10:47.823
And there have been some real success stories of languages that looked

00:10:47.883 --> 00:10:52.223
like they were moving towards becoming extinct, with the number of

00:10:52.223 --> 00:10:57.903
speakers decreasing every year, that have enjoyed a revival, a rebirth.

00:10:58.573 --> 00:11:02.063
In the UK, for instance, you will know that we speak

00:11:02.063 --> 00:11:06.233
English, and it is spoken by 98% of the population.

00:11:06.923 --> 00:11:13.523
But people also speak Scots, Welsh, Scots Gaelic, Irish, and Cornish.

00:11:13.813 --> 00:11:19.003
There has been a concerted effort in the UK to promote these languages,

00:11:19.523 --> 00:11:25.843
with them being taught in schools, used on road signs, and in official

00:11:25.843 --> 00:11:31.003
documentation which is made available in other languages than English

00:11:32.518 --> 00:11:41.158
And in Hawaii, the local language, Hawaiian, was almost completely extinct by the end of the 1980s.

00:11:42.378 --> 00:11:48.028
Some schools had banned it, and English was strongly encouraged.

00:11:49.318 --> 00:11:52.578
There were only a few hundred speakers left, and it

00:11:52.578 --> 00:11:55.948
looked like it was going to die out within a generation.

00:11:56.568 --> 00:12:01.148
However, a few good souls decided to do something about it.

00:12:01.548 --> 00:12:05.558
They opened schools and encouraged children to learn Hawaiian.

00:12:06.248 --> 00:12:13.498
There are now about 25,000 fluent Hawaiian speakers, which of course is nothing compared to the

00:12:13.498 --> 00:12:21.078
number of English speakers, but it is certainly enough to bring it out of the immediate danger zone.

00:12:21.928 --> 00:12:25.888
But what happens when a language does really die though?

00:12:26.608 --> 00:12:31.728
Well, there is one famous example of a language where all

00:12:31.728 --> 00:12:37.418
its speakers did die, but the language today is thriving.

00:12:38.068 --> 00:12:42.768
No, it’s not Latin - I don’t think that people learning it in schools

00:12:42.808 --> 00:12:46.628
and speaking it in the Vatican City can be considered ‘thriving’.

00:12:47.148 --> 00:12:50.578
It’s Hebrew, an official language of Israel.

00:12:51.958 --> 00:13:00.488
Hebrew hadn’t been a spoken language for communication purposes since the second century AD, but

00:13:00.898 --> 00:13:08.018
had been preserved in religious texts, and it had been spoken in prayers and religious services.

00:13:08.618 --> 00:13:12.938
But that was it - people didn’t speak it in their day to day lives.

00:13:13.548 --> 00:13:18.228
Towards the end of the 19th century, there were large efforts to

00:13:18.538 --> 00:13:24.798
revive the language, and it’s now spoken by 90% of Israeli Jews.

00:13:25.598 --> 00:13:32.548
Interestingly enough, when the language was revived, they had to come up with all these new words

00:13:32.778 --> 00:13:40.078
for things that just didn’t exist when the language stopped being spoken, 1700 years before.

00:13:40.908 --> 00:13:47.078
So they had to invent entirely new words for things like the tomato, which had

00:13:47.308 --> 00:13:51.948
only been introduced to Israel after having been brought back from the Americas.

00:13:52.688 --> 00:13:55.463
And they had to come up for a word for things like

00:13:56.073 --> 00:14:00.278
‘electricity’, which obviously didn’t exist in the 2nd century.

00:14:01.088 --> 00:14:07.178
So, if there is enough will, for whatever reason, just because a language looks

00:14:07.178 --> 00:14:13.898
like it might die out, the process can be stopped, and languages can flourish again.

00:14:14.808 --> 00:14:20.978
Now, we have a plethora of advantages that previous generations didn’t have.

00:14:21.658 --> 00:14:27.368
It’s very easy to record people speaking, so we can preserve how to speak a language.

00:14:28.048 --> 00:14:32.858
And the internet makes it easier than ever for people to connect with each

00:14:32.858 --> 00:14:38.058
other, for speakers of different languages to come together and practice it,

00:14:38.618 --> 00:14:44.148
or at least, to help linguists understand how to preserve those languages.

00:14:44.948 --> 00:14:50.628
However, despite all of these advantages, people need to want to do it.

00:14:51.558 --> 00:14:54.798
Without the people that want to preserve the language

00:14:54.978 --> 00:14:58.528
for future generations, there will be no preserving it.

00:14:59.258 --> 00:15:04.578
The majority of the endangered languages are oral languages, they often

00:15:04.578 --> 00:15:09.388
don’t have written forms, which makes preserving them even harder.

00:15:10.208 --> 00:15:15.918
If every English speaker on the planet died tomorrow, someone could relatively

00:15:15.998 --> 00:15:22.248
easily figure out how to speak English, because there is so much written in English.

00:15:23.238 --> 00:15:29.108
But if nothing is written, then the language dies with its last speaker.

00:15:30.108 --> 00:15:35.568
And this isn’t a rare occurrence only around a third of all world languages

00:15:35.708 --> 00:15:39.778
have written systems, a way of actually writing the language down.

00:15:40.638 --> 00:15:42.568
You might be thinking, ‘so what?

00:15:43.208 --> 00:15:48.918
Languages dying out is just a natural part of the life cycle of the world - instead of

00:15:48.918 --> 00:15:55.168
spending money encouraging people to speak them, why don’t we invest in schools, hospitals,

00:15:55.188 --> 00:16:01.038
or teaching people a more useful language like English, or Spanish, or Mandarin?’

00:16:01.958 --> 00:16:06.718
It also begs the question, why should we actually preserve anything?

00:16:07.608 --> 00:16:12.128
From ancient buildings to sculptures, to wildlife to

00:16:12.128 --> 00:16:16.278
animals, should we interfere with the natural flow of things?

00:16:17.788 --> 00:16:24.268
If you are approaching the subject from a purely utilitarian point of view, saying

00:16:24.278 --> 00:16:29.678
that we should only seek to preserve things that have an immediate use for mankind,

00:16:30.298 --> 00:16:35.038
then you probably don’t think it’s worth battling to preserve a dying language.

00:16:35.698 --> 00:16:39.238
But then, you shouldn’t see any reason to protect a

00:16:39.598 --> 00:16:43.638
beautiful fresco, or to stop the pandas from dying out.

00:16:44.388 --> 00:16:52.279
Languages give us just the most amazing insight into how people, cultures, and society develops.

00:16:53.339 --> 00:16:59.609
The words and expressions that exist in a language tell us about its people - people

00:16:59.609 --> 00:17:05.309
need words to convey meaning, the words in a language tell us what people need to say.

00:17:06.039 --> 00:17:13.619
There’s the quote that you’ve probably heard 1,000 times that Eskimos have 50 different

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:20.389
words for different types of snow, but this kind of idea applies to almost every language.

00:17:21.249 --> 00:17:24.729
In your language, I’m sure there are words and expressions

00:17:25.009 --> 00:17:27.869
that don’t have an exact equivalent in English.

00:17:28.859 --> 00:17:32.779
For example, in a situation where in English you would say

00:17:33.109 --> 00:17:37.459
‘How are you?’, in Mandarin you would say ‘Have you eaten yet?’

00:17:38.139 --> 00:17:41.749
And in Cherokee, a Native American language, there

00:17:41.749 --> 00:17:46.419
is no word for ‘goodbye’, only ‘I’ll see you again’.

00:17:47.479 --> 00:17:51.439
These might be small differences, but they tell us a huge

00:17:51.459 --> 00:17:55.179
amount about the culture and the people that use the language.

00:17:55.909 --> 00:18:01.669
And when the language dies out, and without any real written or recorded evidence of

00:18:01.669 --> 00:18:07.249
how to use it, so dies an important part of our knowledge of the people that spoke it.

00:18:08.279 --> 00:18:13.159
And I, for one, think we should do everything we can to avoid that.

00:18:14.779 --> 00:18:19.779
